query:
How can I fix this Java code to avoid a NullPointerException? "public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = null;
        System.out.println(name.length());
    }
}"

response:
To avoid the NullPointerException, you can either initialize the `name` variable to a non-null value before using it, or add a null check before calling `length()` method.

1. Initialization:
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = "John"; // initialize name to a non-null value
        System.out.println(name.length());
    }
}
```
2. Null check:
```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = null;
        if (name != null) {
            System.out.println(name.length());
        } else {
            System.out.println("Name is null");
        }
    }
}
```
In the second example, the `if` statement checks if `name` is not null before calling the `length()` method. If `name` is null, the code inside the `else` block will execute.

